Revisiting the Removable Partial Denture.

Kim JJ(1).

Author information:
(1)Department of Restorative Dentistry, University of Illinois at Chicago, 801 
South Paulina Street Room 359., Chicago, IL 60612, USA. Electronic address: 
Jkim439@uic.edu.

The partial edentulous population is increasing because of an increasing aging 
population, increased life expectancy, and individuals retaining more teeth at 
an older age. Therefore, the need for fixed and removable partial denture (RPD) 
therapy will remain high and will continue into the future. RPDs provide 
minimally invasive, cost-effective, timely care, and are preferred to fixed 
dental prostheses using teeth or implant therapy in many clinical scenarios. 
This article discusses RPD classification systems to review basic concepts and 
special framework design considerations, and explores advancements in the field 
such as implant-assisted RPD, CAD/CAM RPD, and new polymer framework materials.

